ce:section.ce:para:
The stability of Zn plating and stripping in Zn||Zn symmetric cells and the CE of Zn||Ti half-cells were examined in 2 M ZnSO4 electrolytes with and without F-GQDs additive. First, to optimize the concentration of F-GQDs in the electrolyte, the nucleation overpotentials of Zn||Ti half-cells with different concentrations of F-GQDs were measured at a current density of 1 mA cm−2 during plating on Ti for 10 h. The lowest nucleation overpotential for Zn plating (50 mV) is observed in electrolytes with a F-GQDs concentration of 0.5 mg mL−1 (
                        Fig. S7
                     ). The low nucleation overpotential implies a lower nucleation energy barrier, which is conducive to the Zn nucleation. Moreover, the Nyquist plots show that the lowest charge-transfer resistance is found at a F-GQDs concentration of 0.5 mg mL−1 (
                        Fig. S8
                     ). A too low concentration of F-GQDs in the electrolyte results in the formation of a scattered and inhomogeneous layer of F-GQDs on Ti foil, as reflected by large nucleation voltage (
                        Fig. S7
                     ). The imperfect F-GQDs layer cannot suppress dendrite formation and parasitic reactions at the anode–electrolyte interface. On the other hand, when excessive amounts F-GQDs are added to the electrolyte, the formed F-GQDs layer is too thick and detrimental to the ion-transfer kinetics during Zn plating/stripping processes, as evidenced by large charge-transfer resistance (
                        Fig. S8
                     ).

The efficacy of the F-GQDs dramatically improved the electrochemical stability of the Zn anodes. Fig. 2

                     a displays the voltage curves of Zn||Zn symmetric cells in electrolyte with and without F-GQDs at a current density of 0.5 mA cm−2 and an areal capacity of 0.25 mAh cm−2. The cell assembled with the F-GQDs exhibits a smaller voltage variation than that without them, demonstrating that the F-GQDs lead to a more reversible Zn plating/stripping behavior. More crucially, the F-GQD-containing electrolytes result in higher voltage stability, with a smaller overpotential of 40 mV for 1800 h. In comparison, the battery without F-GQDs fails after 226 h. When the current density reaches 1 mA cm−2, A significant voltage variation was detected after 132 h in symmetric Zn||Zn cells without F-GQDs (
                        Fig. S9
                     ). In contrast, Zn||Zn symmetric cells with F-GQDs exhibit stable operation for more than 1000 h. Impressively, these cells exhibit a lifespan of 450 h at 10 mA cm−2 and a plating/stripping capacity of 5 mAh cm−2 (Fig. 2
                     b). Furthermore, the battery assembled with the F-GQDs-containing electrolyte maintains a stable voltage hysteresis at 81 mV, which is superior to that of the Zn anodes in the electrolyte without F-GQDs (131 mV). This parameter essentially exceeds the general requirements for practical applications, highlighting the outstanding characteristic of a stable interface between anode and electrolyte, which enables stable and rapid charge/discharge cycles. It is worth mentioning that GQDs without functional groups perform poorly in symmetric cells, owing to their weaker electronegativity (
                        Fig. S10
                     ). More surprisingly, even after increasing the current density to 50 mA cm−2 (
                        Fig. S11
                     ), the Zn anode in the symmetrical cell assembled with the optimized electrolyte remains stable for more than 12 h with small voltage fluctuations, outperforming all previously reported Zn metal batteries (
                        Table S1
                     ). The high stability of the Zn anode confirms the reliability of the F-GQDs layers fabricated by in situ electrochemical induction under these severe testing conditions.

To investigate the Zn deposition behavior on the Zn anode, an in situ optical microscope was used to observe the anode–electrolyte interface during Zn plating in 2 M ZnSO4 electrolyte with and without F-GQDs (Fig. 3
a, b). For the electrolyte without F-GQDs (Fig. 3 a), flaky particles of different sizes were observed to grow on the Zn anode surface within 10 min. With increasing plating time, the particles become larger and evolve into larger dendrites after 30 min, because of the well-known tip effect. The formation of dendrites will result in the formation of dead Zn with limited plating/stripping efficiency or in a short circuit. On the other hand, for the electrolyte with added F-GQDs, the anode–electrolyte interface remained flat without any dendrite formation after 30 min, indicating that the F-GQDs support dendrite-free Zn deposition (Fig. 3 b). This emphasizes the need to add F-GQDs for dendrite-free Zn deposition. To evaluate the reliability of the F-GQDs, we characterized the surface of Zn anodes after plating/stripping. The SEM images of the surface of symmetric Zn||Zn cells without F-GQDs after five cycles reveal significant agglomeration of the deposited Zn into large particles with a diameter of up to 50 µm (Fig. 3 c, d), which is consistent with the optical microscopy observations and previously reported results [16,18]. In contrast, the SEM images of the Zn anode surface with F-GQDs show a relatively smooth and compact Zn deposition layer with no protruding dendrites (Fig. 3 e, f). Furthermore, 3D laser microscopy images of cycled Zn in the electrolyte without F-GQDs show a maximum height difference of ∼ 78.8 µm for the surface with dendrites (surface roughness: 42.4 µm) (Fig. 3 g). In contrast, the height difference measured for the Zn-deposited surface of the F-GQDs-decorated Zn anode is ∼ 13.4 µm (surface roughness: 7.1 µm) (Fig. 3 h). Furthermore, energy dispersive spectroscopy (EDS) mapping of the cycled Zn surface with F-GQDs shows the presence of C, N, O, and S elements on the overall surface, indicating the uniform distribution of the F-GQDs ( Fig. S13 ). However, only O and Zn elements can be observed in the EDS mapping of cycled Zn in the electrolyte without F-GQDs ( Fig. S14
). The Raman spectrum of the cycled Zn anode with F-GQDs also reveals the typical graphene characteristics of F-GQDs on Zn foil (Fig. 3 i) [34,41]. Besides, XRD patterns of Zn electrodes before and after cycling in the electrolyte with/without F-GQDs were measured to identify the variation in surface composition ( Fig. S15 ). New diffraction peaks appeared for Zn cycled without F-GQDs (inset of Fig. S15 ), which indicates that Zn4SO4(OH)6·4H2O by-product is generated on Zn due to increased pH value resulting from HER occurrence [20]. In comparison, there is no observable by-product diffraction peak for Zn electrode cycled with F-GQDs, implying high reversibility of Zn plating/stripping reaction by virtue of F-GQDs.
